Just now

--

One of the most useful habits a frontend developer can build is learning how to move before the backend is fully readу
This does not mean ignoring the backend. It does not mean inventing random data and hoping everything will work later. It means building the frontend around an expected contract early enough that the UI, the product flow, and the backend implementation can grow together.
Imagine a very normal task. You need to build a user management page. The design is already approved. The page should show a searchable table of users, role badges, account statuses, loading state, empty state, and pagination. From the frontend side, the job is clear. You know what the user should see. You know how the page should behave. You probably already know which components you will create.
But the endpoint is not ready yet.
Maybe the backend team is still working on permissions. Maybe the database schema is being reviewed. Maybe the endpoint exists locally on someone’s machine but is not deployed to staging. Maybe staging is available, but the data there is useless for testing real UI states.
This is the moment where many frontend developers either wait or start hardcoding fake data inside components. Both approaches can become painful. Waiting slows the team down. Hardcoding makes the code messy.
A better option is to create a local mock endpoint that follows the expected API shape.
Let’s say the future endpoint will look like this:
GET /api/users?page=1&search=sarahAnd the expected response will look like this:
{
"users": [
{
"id": "u_001",
"name": "Sarah Chen",
"email": "sarah@example.com",
"role": "admin",
"status": "active"
}
],
"pagination": {
"page": 1,
"pageSize": 10,
"total": 1
}
}That is already enough to build against. The frontend does not need the final database implementation. It needs a reliable response contract.
