Caption: A realistic mock endpoint lets the frontend behave as if the real API already exists.
The mock route can be simple, but it should behave enough like the real endpoint to make the UI useful.
mock.route("GET", "/api/users", ({ query }) => {
const page = Number(query.page || 1);
const search = String(query.search || "").toLowerCase(); const allUsers = [
{
id: "u_001",
name: "Sarah Chen",
email: "sarah@example.com",
role: "admin",
status: "active"
},
{
id: "u_002",
name: "David Kim",
email: "david@example.com",
role: "editor",
status: "invited"
},
{
id: "u_003",
name: "Maya Patel",
email: "maya@example.com",
role: "viewer",
status: "disabled"
},
{
id: "u_004",
name: "Christopher Alexander Montgomery-Smith",
email: "christopher.montgomery.smith@very-long-company-domain.com",
role: "administrator",
status: "pending_review"
}
]; const filteredUsers = allUsers.filter((user) =>
user.name.toLowerCase().includes(search)
); return {
status: 200,
delay: 500,
body: {
users: filteredUsers,
pagination: {
page,
pageSize: 10,
total: filteredUsers.length
}
}
};
});This is not a full backend. It does not need to be. But it gives the frontend enough reality to work with. The table can render different roles. The search input can update the response. The UI can show a long email and reveal layout problems. The loading state can become visible because of the delay.
Now the actual frontend code can stay clean.
const response = await fetch("/api/users?page=1&search=sarah");
const data = await response.json();The component does not need to know whether the response came from a mock or a real backend. That is the important part. Your UI should not be full of conditions like isMockMode or useFakeUsers. It should talk to an API. During development, the API can be local. Later, it can be real.
This approach also helps the team have better conversations. A designer can review how long names behave in the table. A product manager can check whether the empty state copy makes sense. QA can test invited, disabled, and active users without waiting for staging to contain exactly the right data.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Caption: Realistic mock data helps reveal layout issues before real users find them.
The most important detail is that the mock should stay close to the real API contract. When the backend becomes ready, you do not want to discover that the frontend was built around a completely different response shape. If the real API returns users, the mock should return users. If the backend uses totalCount, the mock should probably use totalCount too. Small naming differences create annoying integration bugs later.
Mocking is not about pretending integration will be perfect. It will not be. The backend may still change. Some field names may move. Permissions may affect the response. Authentication may add complexity. But even with those changes, the frontend work is not wasted. The layout, user flow, loading state, empty state, and component behavior are already built.
That is the real value.
Building UI before the API is ready does not mean building fake UI. It means building real UI against a temporary but realistic version of the API contract. It keeps the frontend moving, gives the team something concrete to review, and makes backend integration less stressful when the real endpoint finally arrives.
